00:05:45.630 --> 00:05:54.020
But basically, let me just
try to elaborate on --

00:05:54.020 --> 00:06:02.030
probability theory is a
conceptual framework that

00:06:02.030 --> 00:06:05.090
mathematicians invented.

00:06:05.090 --> 00:06:10.970
And it's become a very important
way of thinking, but

00:06:10.970 --> 00:06:13.950
it doesn't go back
that far in time.

00:06:13.950 --> 00:06:18.890
The word probability in its
present meaning wasn't even

00:06:18.890 --> 00:06:21.510
coined until the 1600's.

00:06:21.510 --> 00:06:27.080
So, you if you talk to someone
before the year 1600, and say,

00:06:27.080 --> 00:06:31.240
this has a probability of 0.5,
they would have no idea what

00:06:31.240 --> 00:06:32.650
you're talking about.

00:06:32.650 --> 00:06:36.380
So, it's a major advance in
human understanding to think

00:06:36.380 --> 00:06:38.280
in terms of probabilities.

00:06:38.280 --> 00:06:39.440
Now we do.

00:06:39.440 --> 00:06:43.270
And now it's routine, but it
wasn't routine at all.

00:06:43.270 --> 00:06:48.880
And part of what I'm thinking
about is, what probability

00:06:48.880 --> 00:06:53.550
theorists do, or in particular
finance theorists like to do,

00:06:53.550 --> 00:06:57.590
is they think that the world
is, well, let me just say,

00:06:57.590 --> 00:07:02.180
it's kind of a realization
that the world is very

00:07:02.180 --> 00:07:08.300
complex, and that the outcomes
that we see are the results of

00:07:08.300 --> 00:07:12.250
millions of little things.

00:07:12.250 --> 00:07:15.920
And the stories we tell
are just stories.

00:07:15.920 --> 00:07:19.330
So, how do we deal with the
complexity of the world?

00:07:19.330 --> 00:07:23.330
Well, we do it by dealing
with all of these little

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:27.990
incremental shocks that
affect our lives in a

00:07:27.990 --> 00:07:28.960
mathematical way.

00:07:28.960 --> 00:07:31.660
And we think of them as
millions of shocks.

00:07:31.660 --> 00:07:34.160
How do they accumulate?

00:07:34.160 --> 00:07:37.950
We have mathematical laws
of how they accumulate.

00:07:37.950 --> 00:07:46.230
And once we understand those
laws, we can we can build

00:07:46.230 --> 00:07:48.870
mathematical models
of the outcomes.

00:07:48.870 --> 00:07:54.750
And then we can ask whether we
should be surprised by the

00:07:54.750 --> 00:07:57.050
financial events that
we've seen.

00:07:57.050 --> 00:08:01.740
It's a little bit like science,
real hard science.

00:08:01.740 --> 00:08:04.990
So, for example, weather
forecasters.

00:08:04.990 --> 00:08:06.980
They build models that
-- you know, you see

00:08:06.980 --> 00:08:08.320
these weather forecasts.

00:08:08.320 --> 00:08:13.140
They have computer models that
are built on the theory of

00:08:13.140 --> 00:08:15.280
fluid dynamics.

00:08:15.280 --> 00:08:18.670
And there is a theory of all
those little atoms moving

00:08:18.670 --> 00:08:20.090
around in the air.

00:08:20.090 --> 00:08:27.400
And there's too many atoms to
count, but there's some laws

00:08:27.400 --> 00:08:30.230
about their cumulative movement
that we understand.

00:08:30.230 --> 00:08:34.300
And it actually allows us
to forecast the weather.

00:08:34.300 --> 00:08:39.350
And so, people who are steeped
in this tradition in finance

00:08:39.350 --> 00:08:42.810
think that what we're doing
when we're doing financial

00:08:42.810 --> 00:08:45.120
forecast is very much
like what we do when

00:08:45.120 --> 00:08:46.680
we do weather forecasts.

00:08:46.680 --> 00:08:49.150
We have a statistical model,
we see all of the shocks

00:08:49.150 --> 00:08:54.810
coming in, and of course there
will be hurricanes.

00:08:54.810 --> 00:08:57.830
And we can only forecast them --
you know there's a limit to

00:08:57.830 --> 00:09:00.240
how far out we can
forecast them.

00:09:00.240 --> 00:09:03.740
So, all hurricanes are
a surprise two

00:09:03.740 --> 00:09:05.530
weeks before they happen.

00:09:05.530 --> 00:09:08.410
Weather forecasters
can't do that.

00:09:08.410 --> 00:09:10.560
Same thing with financial
crises.

00:09:10.560 --> 00:09:12.260
This would be the model.

00:09:12.260 --> 00:09:15.780
We understand the probability
laws, there's only a certain

00:09:15.780 --> 00:09:18.580
time horizon before which
we can forecast

00:09:18.580 --> 00:09:20.290
the financial crisis.

00:09:23.880 --> 00:09:26.680
That isn't exactly my view
of the situation.

00:09:26.680 --> 00:09:29.230
I'm presenting a view this
time which is very

00:09:29.230 --> 00:09:34.340
mathematical and probability
theory oriented.

00:09:34.340 --> 00:09:36.770
So, let me get into some
of these details.

00:09:36.770 --> 00:09:40.320
And again, these are going to
be re-covered in the review

00:09:40.320 --> 00:09:43.560
session that Elan Fuld,
one of our teaching

00:09:43.560 --> 00:09:44.810
assistants, will do.

