I have just slides with
graphs and equations.

00:09:52.220 --> 00:09:57.220
But, that's not Elan Fuld.

00:09:57.220 --> 00:10:01.950
I want to start out with just
the concept of return.

00:10:01.950 --> 00:10:06.920
Which is, in finance, the
basic, the most basic

00:10:06.920 --> 00:10:08.400
concept that --

00:10:08.400 --> 00:10:13.290
[SIDE CONVERSATION]

00:10:13.290 --> 00:10:15.350
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: When
you invest in something, you

00:10:15.350 --> 00:10:18.190
have to do it for
a time interval.

00:10:18.190 --> 00:10:21.520
And I'm writing the return
as one time period.

00:10:21.520 --> 00:10:23.600
T is time.

00:10:23.600 --> 00:10:26.310
And so, it could be a year, or
it could be months, or it

00:10:26.310 --> 00:10:27.560
could be a day.

00:10:34.590 --> 00:10:37.390
We're going to number these
months, let's say it's monthly

00:10:37.390 --> 00:10:49.210
return, we're going to number
these months, so that the

00:10:49.210 --> 00:10:52.180
first month is number one,
second month is number two.

00:10:52.180 --> 00:10:56.420
And so, return at time t, if t
is equal to 3, that would be

00:10:56.420 --> 00:11:00.070
the return at month three.

00:11:00.070 --> 00:11:02.610
And we'll do price at the
beginning of the month.

00:11:02.610 --> 00:11:06.230
And so, what is your return
to investing in something?

00:11:06.230 --> 00:11:09.660
It's the increase
in the price.

00:11:09.660 --> 00:11:13.140
That's p t plus 1, minus p t.

00:11:13.140 --> 00:11:15.310
I'm spelling it out here.

00:11:15.310 --> 00:11:16.170
Price --

00:11:16.170 --> 00:11:18.180
I spelled it out in the
numerator, I guess I didn't do

00:11:18.180 --> 00:11:19.430
it in the denominator.

00:11:21.440 --> 00:11:24.870
It's price at time t plus 1
minus the price at time t,

00:11:24.870 --> 00:11:28.040
which is called the capital
gain, plus the dividend, which

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:33.460
is a check you receive, if you
do, from the company that

00:11:33.460 --> 00:11:36.470
you're investing in.

00:11:36.470 --> 00:11:39.360
That's the return.

00:11:39.360 --> 00:11:41.240
We have something else
called gross return.

00:11:41.240 --> 00:11:43.480
Which is just 1 plus
the return.

00:11:43.480 --> 00:11:45.280
Returns can be positive
or negative.

00:11:45.280 --> 00:11:49.880
They can never be more than --
never be less than minus 100%.

00:11:49.880 --> 00:11:54.630
In a limited liability economy
that we live in, the law says

00:11:54.630 --> 00:11:57.380
that you cannot lose more than
the money you put in, and

00:11:57.380 --> 00:12:00.420
that's going to be
our assumption.

00:12:00.420 --> 00:12:05.290
So, return is between minus
100% and plus infinity.

00:12:05.290 --> 00:12:08.400
And gross return is
always positive.

00:12:08.400 --> 00:12:10.730
It's between zero
and infinity.

00:12:13.470 --> 00:12:15.710
Now what we're going to do --

00:12:15.710 --> 00:12:20.150
this is the primary thing that
we want to study, because we

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:25.460
are interested in investing
and in making a return.

00:12:25.460 --> 00:12:30.530
So, we want to do some
evaluations of the success of

00:12:30.530 --> 00:12:33.110
an investment.

00:12:33.110 --> 00:12:37.580
So, I want to now talk about
some basic statistical

00:12:37.580 --> 00:12:43.330
concepts that we can apply to
returns and to other random

00:12:43.330 --> 00:12:44.580
variables as well.

00:12:47.220 --> 00:12:49.480
These on this slide are
mostly concepts that

00:12:49.480 --> 00:12:51.490
you've already heard.

00:12:51.490 --> 00:12:54.410
This is expected value.

00:12:54.410 --> 00:12:58.560
This is the mathematical
expectation of a random

00:12:58.560 --> 00:13:04.110
variable x, which could be the
return, or the gross return,

00:13:04.110 --> 00:13:05.942
or something else, but
we're going to

00:13:05.942 --> 00:13:07.750
substitute something else.

00:13:07.750 --> 00:13:09.770
We're going to substitute
in what they are.

00:13:09.770 --> 00:13:13.410
So, the expectation of x, or
the mean of x, mu sub x is

00:13:13.410 --> 00:13:17.900
another term for it, is the
weighted sum of all possible

00:13:17.900 --> 00:13:21.960
values of x weighted by
their probabilities.

00:13:21.960 --> 00:13:24.690
And the probabilities
have to sum to 1.

00:13:24.690 --> 00:13:30.930
They're positive numbers, or
zero or positive numbers,

00:13:30.930 --> 00:13:34.280
reflecting the likelihood
of that random variable

00:13:34.280 --> 00:13:39.010
occurring, of that value of the
random variable occurring.

00:13:39.010 --> 00:13:39.900
So, I have here --

00:13:39.900 --> 00:13:45.960
there's an infinite number of
possible values for x, and we

00:13:45.960 --> 00:13:50.430
have a probability for each one,
and the expectation of x

00:13:50.430 --> 00:13:54.290
is that weighted sum of those,
weighted by probabilities, of

00:13:54.290 --> 00:13:55.920
those possible values.

00:13:55.920 --> 00:14:00.240
This is for a discrete random
variable that takes on only a

00:14:00.240 --> 00:14:04.250
finite, only a countable
number of values.

00:14:04.250 --> 00:14:09.080
If it's a continuous random
variable, if x is continuous,

00:14:09.080 --> 00:14:16.390
then the expectation of x is an
integral of the probability

00:14:16.390 --> 00:14:20.440
density of x, times x dx.

00:14:20.440 --> 00:14:23.650
I'm just writing that down for
you now for completeness.

00:14:23.650 --> 00:14:26.273
But I'm not going to explain
or elaborate that.

00:14:29.380 --> 00:14:35.750
These two formulas here are
measures of the central

00:14:35.750 --> 00:14:40.060
tendency of x, OK.

00:14:40.060 --> 00:14:49.250
It's essentially the average of
x in the probability metric

00:14:49.250 --> 00:14:51.310
that we have up here.

00:14:51.310 --> 00:14:55.100
But this formula is something
we use to estimate the

00:14:55.100 --> 00:14:56.350
expected value of x.

00:14:59.140 --> 00:15:01.690
This is called the mean or
average, which you've

00:15:01.690 --> 00:15:03.450
learned long ago.

00:15:03.450 --> 00:15:08.720
If you have n observations on
a random variable x, you can

00:15:08.720 --> 00:15:12.670
take the sum of the x
observations, summation over i

00:15:12.670 --> 00:15:16.050
equals 1 to n, and then
divide that by n.

00:15:16.050 --> 00:15:17.740
That's called the average.

00:15:17.740 --> 00:15:22.260
So, what I want to say is that
this is the average, or the

00:15:22.260 --> 00:15:25.810
mean, or sample mean when
you have a sample of n

00:15:25.810 --> 00:15:28.910
observations, which is
an estimate of the

00:15:28.910 --> 00:15:31.230
expected value of x.

00:15:31.230 --> 00:15:35.160
So, for example, if we're
evaluating an investor who has

00:15:35.160 --> 00:15:40.010
invested money, you could get n
observations, say an annual

00:15:40.010 --> 00:15:42.840
returns, and you can take
an average of them.

00:15:42.840 --> 00:15:46.630
And that's the first and most
obvious metric representing

00:15:46.630 --> 00:15:53.230
the success of the investments
if x is the return, OK.

00:15:53.230 --> 00:15:54.950
People are always wanting to
know, they're looking at

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:58.740
someone who invests money, is
this person a success or not?

00:15:58.740 --> 00:16:00.890
Well this is the first and
most obvious measure.

00:16:00.890 --> 00:16:03.020
Let's see what that person
did on average.

00:16:03.020 --> 00:16:07.010
You were investing for, let's
say n equals 10, ten years,

00:16:07.010 --> 00:16:10.290
let's take the returns you made
each year, add them up

00:16:10.290 --> 00:16:12.370
and divide by 10.

00:16:12.370 --> 00:16:14.610
And that gives us an average.

00:16:14.610 --> 00:16:17.970
I put this formula down as
an alternative, because

00:16:17.970 --> 00:16:19.690
it's another --

00:16:19.690 --> 00:16:22.370
this is called the
geometric mean.

00:16:22.370 --> 00:16:24.680
This is the arithmetic mean.

00:16:24.680 --> 00:16:27.170
This is the geometric mean and
you're probably not so

00:16:27.170 --> 00:16:31.170
familiar with that, because
it's a different concept.

00:16:31.170 --> 00:16:35.730
The geometric mean, instead of
adding your n observations,

00:16:35.730 --> 00:16:37.600
you multiply them together.

00:16:37.600 --> 00:16:40.120
You form a product of them.

00:16:40.120 --> 00:16:44.810
And then, instead of dividing by
n, you take the nth root of

00:16:44.810 --> 00:16:45.990
the product.

00:16:45.990 --> 00:16:49.720
And so, that's a formula that's
used to estimate the

00:16:49.720 --> 00:16:54.520
average return of a portfolio
of investments, where we use

00:16:54.520 --> 00:17:01.030
gross return for x, not just
the simple return.

00:17:01.030 --> 00:17:06.340
This geometric mean makes sense
only when all the x's

00:17:06.340 --> 00:17:08.300
are non-negative.

00:17:08.300 --> 00:17:10.030
If you put in a negative
value, you might get a

00:17:10.030 --> 00:17:13.890
negative product, and then, if
you took the nth root of that,

00:17:13.890 --> 00:17:16.840
it could be an imaginary number,
so let's forget that.

00:17:16.840 --> 00:17:19.510
We're not going to apply this
formula if there are any

00:17:19.510 --> 00:17:21.630
negative numbers.

00:17:21.630 --> 00:17:25.440
But it's often used, and
I recommend its use, in

00:17:25.440 --> 00:17:27.520
evaluating investments.

00:17:27.520 --> 00:17:31.760
Because if you use gross return,
it gives a better

00:17:31.760 --> 00:17:34.720
measure of the outcome
of the investments.

00:17:34.720 --> 00:17:35.870
So, think of it this way.

00:17:35.870 --> 00:17:40.150
Suppose you invested money with
some investment manager,

00:17:40.150 --> 00:17:42.900
and the guy said, I've
done a wonderful job

00:17:42.900 --> 00:17:44.390
investing your money.

00:17:44.390 --> 00:17:49.000
I made 50% one year, I made 30%
another year, oh, and by

00:17:49.000 --> 00:17:54.830
the way, I had one bad year
with minus 100%, OK.

00:17:54.830 --> 00:17:57.100
So, what do you think
of this investor?

00:17:57.100 --> 00:18:00.920
Well, if you think about it, if
he made 50% one year, and

00:18:00.920 --> 00:18:04.046
then 30% another year, and
then he lost everything.

00:18:06.980 --> 00:18:08.700
That dominates everything,
right?

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:12.360
If you have a minus 100% simple
return, your gross

00:18:12.360 --> 00:18:14.550
return is 0, OK?

00:18:14.550 --> 00:18:18.900
So, if I plug in, if I put in
a 0 here to any of the x's,

00:18:18.900 --> 00:18:23.250
right, this product will be 0.

00:18:23.250 --> 00:18:25.440
Anything times 0 is 0.

00:18:25.440 --> 00:18:27.490
And I take the nth root of
zero, and what's that?

00:18:27.490 --> 00:18:28.900
It's 0.

00:18:28.900 --> 00:18:32.230
So, if there's ever a year in
which the return is minus

00:18:32.230 --> 00:18:38.490
100%, then the geometric
mean is 0.

00:18:38.490 --> 00:18:39.820
That's a good discipline.

00:18:39.820 --> 00:18:43.250
This obviously doesn't make
sense as a way to evaluate

00:18:43.250 --> 00:18:44.360
investment success.

00:18:44.360 --> 00:18:45.940
Are you with me on this?

00:18:45.940 --> 00:18:50.750
Because you care a lot, if
the guy wipes you out.

00:18:50.750 --> 00:18:54.110
Whatever else is done after
that doesn't matter.

00:18:54.110 --> 00:18:58.430
So, that's why we want to use
the geometric return.

00:19:02.110 --> 00:19:04.920
These are all measures
of central tendency.

00:19:04.920 --> 00:19:08.230
That is, what is the
central result?

00:19:08.230 --> 00:19:10.560
Sometimes the investor had a
good year, sometimes the

00:19:10.560 --> 00:19:13.520
investor had a bad year, but
what was the typical or

00:19:13.520 --> 00:19:15.590
central value?

00:19:15.590 --> 00:19:18.840
So, these are a couple
of measures of them.

00:19:18.840 --> 00:19:21.890
But we care about more than just
about central tendency

00:19:21.890 --> 00:19:23.810
when evaluating risk.

00:19:23.810 --> 00:19:26.540
We have to do other
things as well.

00:19:26.540 --> 00:19:29.420
And so, you want to talk about
-- and this is very

00:19:29.420 --> 00:19:30.900
fundamental to finance.

00:19:30.900 --> 00:19:32.540
We have to talk about risk.

00:19:32.540 --> 00:19:37.180
What could be more fundamental
than risk for finance?

00:19:37.180 --> 00:19:41.890
So, what we have here now is
a measure of variability.

00:19:41.890 --> 00:19:48.010
And the upper equation here is
something called variance.

00:19:48.010 --> 00:19:56.380
And it's equal to the weighted
average of the x random

00:19:56.380 --> 00:19:56.608
variables [correction:
realizations of

00:19:56.608 --> 00:19:57.300
the x random variable]

00:19:57.300 --> 00:20:00.200
squared deviation from
the mean, weighted by

00:20:00.200 --> 00:20:02.010
probabilities.

00:20:02.010 --> 00:20:03.150
OK?

00:20:03.150 --> 00:20:09.180
All it is, is the expectation of
the square of the deviation

00:20:09.180 --> 00:20:11.100
from the mean.

00:20:11.100 --> 00:20:16.820
The mean is the center value,
and the deviations from the

00:20:16.820 --> 00:20:18.070
mean are --

00:20:21.140 --> 00:20:23.380
whether they're positive or
negative, if you square them

00:20:23.380 --> 00:20:25.820
they become positive numbers.

00:20:25.820 --> 00:20:30.670
And so, that's called
variance.

00:20:30.670 --> 00:20:33.650
So, for example, if
x tends to be --

00:20:33.650 --> 00:20:38.240
if the return tends to
be plus or minus 1%

00:20:38.240 --> 00:20:40.630
from the mean return...

00:20:40.630 --> 00:20:45.790
say the mean return for an
investor is 8% a year, and

00:20:45.790 --> 00:20:50.190
it's plus or minus 1%, then
you would see a lot of 1's

00:20:50.190 --> 00:20:53.440
when you squared the deviation
from the mean.

00:20:53.440 --> 00:20:55.860
And the variance would
probably be 1.

00:20:55.860 --> 00:20:59.030
And the standard deviation,
which is --

00:20:59.030 --> 00:21:03.670
the standard deviation is the
square root of the variance.

00:21:03.670 --> 00:21:07.350
And it would also be 1.

00:21:07.350 --> 00:21:08.430
OK.

00:21:08.430 --> 00:21:09.920
This is a very simple concept.

00:21:09.920 --> 00:21:14.250
It's just the average squared
deviation from the mean.

00:21:14.250 --> 00:21:18.930
The estimate of the variance,
or the sample variance, is

00:21:18.930 --> 00:21:21.040
given by this equation.

00:21:21.040 --> 00:21:23.160
And it's s squared of x.

00:21:23.160 --> 00:21:25.160
It's just the sample mean.

00:21:25.160 --> 00:21:30.320
Take deviations of the variable
from its sample mean.

00:21:30.320 --> 00:21:33.480
You have n observations, say
someone has invested money for

00:21:33.480 --> 00:21:38.080
ten years, you take the average
return for the ten

00:21:38.080 --> 00:21:43.170
years and that's x bar, and
then you take all 10

00:21:43.170 --> 00:21:49.580
deviations from the mean
and square them, and

00:21:49.580 --> 00:21:50.640
then divide by n.

00:21:50.640 --> 00:21:53.600
Some people divide by n minus
1, but I'm just trying to be

00:21:53.600 --> 00:21:59.030
very basic and simple here, so
I'm not going to get into

00:21:59.030 --> 00:22:02.785
these ideas.

00:22:05.310 --> 00:22:07.510
The next thing is covariance.

00:22:07.510 --> 00:22:08.870
We're getting through
these concepts.

00:22:08.870 --> 00:22:10.710
They're very basic concepts.

00:22:10.710 --> 00:22:15.630
Covariance is a measure of how
two different random variables

00:22:15.630 --> 00:22:18.430
move together.

00:22:18.430 --> 00:22:22.380
So, I have two different random
variables, x and y.

00:22:22.380 --> 00:22:30.000
So, x is the return on, let's
say, the IBM Corporation, and

00:22:30.000 --> 00:22:34.490
y is the return on General
Motors Corporation.

00:22:34.490 --> 00:22:39.330
And I want to know, when IBM
goes up, does General Motors

00:22:39.330 --> 00:22:41.340
go up or not?

00:22:41.340 --> 00:22:47.600
So, a measure of the co-movement
of the two would

00:22:47.600 --> 00:22:53.500
be to take the deviation of
x from its mean times the

00:22:53.500 --> 00:22:58.600
deviation of y from it's
mean, and take the

00:22:58.600 --> 00:23:01.210
average product of those.

00:23:01.210 --> 00:23:03.060
And that's called covariance.

00:23:03.060 --> 00:23:07.750
It's a positive number if, when
x is high relative to

00:23:07.750 --> 00:23:11.660
it's mean, y is high relative
to its mean also.

00:23:11.660 --> 00:23:14.550
And it's a negative number if
they tend to go in opposite

00:23:14.550 --> 00:23:15.550
directions.

00:23:15.550 --> 00:23:21.080
If GM tends to do well when IBM
does poorly, then we have

00:23:21.080 --> 00:23:22.870
a negative covariance.

00:23:22.870 --> 00:23:25.790
Because, if one is above its
mean, and the other is below

00:23:25.790 --> 00:23:29.050
its mean, the product is going
to be a negative number.

00:23:29.050 --> 00:23:32.760
If we get a lot of negative
products like that, it means

00:23:32.760 --> 00:23:35.920
that they tend to move
opposite each other.

00:23:35.920 --> 00:23:39.490
And if they are unrelated
to each other, then the

00:23:39.490 --> 00:23:43.000
covariance tends to be 0.

00:23:43.000 --> 00:23:46.200
And this is the core concept
that I was talking about.

00:23:46.200 --> 00:23:49.940
Some idea of unrelatedness
underlies a lot of our

00:23:49.940 --> 00:23:52.190
thinking in risk.

00:23:52.190 --> 00:23:55.090
So, if x and y are independent,

00:23:55.090 --> 00:23:56.230
they're generated --

00:23:56.230 --> 00:23:59.730
suppose IBM's business has just
nothing at all to do with

00:23:59.730 --> 00:24:01.790
GM's businesses, they're
so different.

00:24:01.790 --> 00:24:05.800
Then I'd say the covariance
is probably 0.

00:24:05.800 --> 00:24:14.900
And then we can use that as a
principle, which will underlie

00:24:14.900 --> 00:24:17.790
our later analysis.

00:24:17.790 --> 00:24:21.650
Correlation is a scaled
covariance.

00:24:21.650 --> 00:24:25.630
And it's a measure of how much
two variables move together.

00:24:25.630 --> 00:24:29.810
But it's scaled, so that it
varies only over the range of

00:24:29.810 --> 00:24:32.380
minus 1 to plus 1.

00:24:32.380 --> 00:24:35.990
So, the correlation between two
random variables is their

00:24:35.990 --> 00:24:40.400
covariance divided by the
product of their standard

00:24:40.400 --> 00:24:41.540
deviations.

00:24:41.540 --> 00:24:45.220
And you can show that that
always ranges between minus 1

00:24:45.220 --> 00:24:46.610
and plus 1.

00:24:46.610 --> 00:24:51.800
So, if two variables have a plus
1 correlation, that means

00:24:51.800 --> 00:24:53.425
they move exactly together.

00:24:55.950 --> 00:25:00.550
When one moves up 5%, the other
one moves up 5% exactly.

00:25:00.550 --> 00:25:04.590
If they have a correlation of
minus 1, it means the move

00:25:04.590 --> 00:25:06.840
exactly opposite each other.

00:25:06.840 --> 00:25:09.270
These things don't happen very
often in finance, but in

00:25:09.270 --> 00:25:10.800
theory that's what happens.

00:25:10.800 --> 00:25:13.710
If they have a zero correlation,
that means

00:25:13.710 --> 00:25:18.900
there's no tendency for them
to move together at all.

00:25:18.900 --> 00:25:21.830
If two variables are
independent, then their

00:25:21.830 --> 00:25:23.550
correlation should be zero.

00:25:28.210 --> 00:25:37.240
OK, the variance of the sum of
two random variables is the

00:25:37.240 --> 00:25:40.940
variance of the first random
variable, plus the variance of

00:25:40.940 --> 00:25:45.500
the second random variable, plus
twice the covariance of

00:25:45.500 --> 00:25:47.450
the random variables.

00:25:47.450 --> 00:25:50.190
So, if the two random variables
are independent of

00:25:50.190 --> 00:25:53.700
each other, then their
covariance is zero, and then

00:25:53.700 --> 00:25:57.930
the variance of the sum is
the sum of the variances.

00:25:57.930 --> 00:26:00.140
But that is not necessary.

00:26:00.140 --> 00:26:06.860
That's true if the random
variables are independent, but

00:26:06.860 --> 00:26:08.900
we're going to see that
breakdown of independence is

00:26:08.900 --> 00:26:10.600
the story of this lecture
right now.

00:26:13.260 --> 00:26:16.150
We want to think about
independence

00:26:16.150 --> 00:26:19.210
as mattering a lot.

00:26:19.210 --> 00:26:23.250
And it's a model, or a core
idea, but when do we know that

00:26:23.250 --> 00:26:24.500
things are independent?

00:26:28.590 --> 00:26:31.090
OK, this is a plot.

00:26:31.090 --> 00:26:33.580
I was telling you earlier
about the --

00:26:36.430 --> 00:26:45.360
let me see, OK, let me just
hold off on that a minute.

00:26:54.050 --> 00:26:55.140
Well, I'll tell you
what that was.

00:26:55.140 --> 00:26:59.950
That was a plot of the stock
market from 2000 to 2010 in

00:26:59.950 --> 00:27:03.040
the U.S. And I'm going
to come back to that.

00:27:03.040 --> 00:27:04.950
These are the crises I was
telling you about.

00:27:04.950 --> 00:27:09.860
This is the decline in the stock
market from 2000 to 2002

00:27:09.860 --> 00:27:12.670
or 2003 and this is the
more recent decline

00:27:12.670 --> 00:27:17.190
from 2007 to 2009.

00:27:17.190 --> 00:27:21.420
Those are the cumulative effects
of a lot of little

00:27:21.420 --> 00:27:25.160
shocks that didn't happen
all at once.

00:27:25.160 --> 00:27:26.640
It happened over years.

00:27:26.640 --> 00:27:29.380
And we want to think about
the probability of

00:27:29.380 --> 00:27:30.690
those shocks occurring.

00:27:33.530 --> 00:27:41.830
And that's where I am going.

00:27:41.830 --> 00:27:51.440
But what I want to talk about
is the core concept of

00:27:51.440 --> 00:28:02.020
independence leading to some
basic principles of risk

00:28:02.020 --> 00:28:03.610
management.

00:28:03.610 --> 00:28:09.220
The crisis that we've seen here
in the stock market is

00:28:09.220 --> 00:28:11.230
the accumulation of --

00:28:11.230 --> 00:28:15.740
you see all these ups and downs
in the stock market, and

00:28:15.740 --> 00:28:21.820
then all these ups and
downs on the way up.

00:28:21.820 --> 00:28:25.450
There were relatively more downs
in the period from 2000

00:28:25.450 --> 00:28:29.170
and 2002 and there were
relatively more ups from the

00:28:29.170 --> 00:28:33.300
period 2003 to 2006.

00:28:33.300 --> 00:28:36.710
But how do we understand the
cumulative effect of it, which

00:28:36.710 --> 00:28:37.450
is what matters?

00:28:37.450 --> 00:28:43.690
So, we have to have some kind
of probability Model.

00:28:43.690 --> 00:28:48.130
The question immediately is, are
these shocks that affected

00:28:48.130 --> 00:29:01.580
the stock market, are they
independent, or are they

00:29:01.580 --> 00:29:05.010
somehow related to each other?

00:29:05.010 --> 00:29:10.670
And that is a core question that
made it so difficult for

00:29:10.670 --> 00:29:13.960
us to understand how to deal
with the potential of such a

00:29:13.960 --> 00:29:19.760
crisis, and why so many people
got in trouble dealing with

00:29:19.760 --> 00:29:21.010
this crisis.

00:29:24.600 --> 00:29:36.820
So, we had a big financial
crisis in the United States in

00:29:36.820 --> 00:29:40.510
1987, when there was a stock
market crash that was bigger

00:29:40.510 --> 00:29:42.630
than any before in one day.

00:29:42.630 --> 00:29:45.510
We'll be talking about that.

00:29:45.510 --> 00:29:57.960
But after the 1987 crash,
companies started to compute a

00:29:57.960 --> 00:30:02.060
measure of the risk to their
company, which is

00:30:02.060 --> 00:30:04.770
called Value at Risk.

00:30:04.770 --> 00:30:07.350
I'll write it up like that.

00:30:07.350 --> 00:30:10.960
I capitalized the first and
the last letter, so you'll

00:30:10.960 --> 00:30:12.520
know that I'm not --
this is not the

00:30:12.520 --> 00:30:14.090
same thing as variance.

00:30:14.090 --> 00:30:16.230
This is Value at Risk.

00:30:23.080 --> 00:30:28.240
And what companies would do
after 1987 to try to measure

00:30:28.240 --> 00:30:35.610
the risk of their activities
is to compute a number

00:30:35.610 --> 00:30:36.570
something like this.

00:30:36.570 --> 00:30:44.670
They would say, there's a 5%
probability that we will lose

00:30:44.670 --> 00:30:51.760
$10 million in a year.

00:30:51.760 --> 00:30:54.810
That's the kind of bottom
line that Value at Risk

00:30:54.810 --> 00:30:57.020
calculations would make.

00:31:00.620 --> 00:31:05.350
And so, you need a probability
Model to make these

00:31:05.350 --> 00:31:07.660
calculations.

00:31:07.660 --> 00:31:15.420
And so, you need probability
theory in order to do that.

00:31:15.420 --> 00:31:21.240
Many companies had calculated
Value at Risk numbers like

00:31:21.240 --> 00:31:25.030
this, and told their investors,
we can't do too

00:31:25.030 --> 00:31:28.690
badly because there's no way
that we could lose --

00:31:28.690 --> 00:31:30.715
the probability is
only 5% that we

00:31:30.715 --> 00:31:31.840
could lose $10 million.

00:31:31.840 --> 00:31:33.640
And they'd have other
numbers like this.

00:31:33.640 --> 00:31:37.470
But they were implicitly making
assumptions about

00:31:37.470 --> 00:31:41.970
independence, or at least
relative independence.

00:31:41.970 --> 00:31:49.860
And that's the concept I'm
trying to emphasize here.

00:31:49.860 --> 00:31:52.600
It's a core concept
in finance.

00:31:52.600 --> 00:32:01.500
And it's not one that is easy
to be precise about.

00:32:01.500 --> 00:32:06.220
We have an intuitive idea that,
you know -- we see the

00:32:06.220 --> 00:32:08.910
ups and downs on the stock
market, and we notice them,

00:32:08.910 --> 00:32:13.120
and they all average out to
something not too bad.

00:32:13.120 --> 00:32:17.440
The problem that brought us this
crisis is that the Value

00:32:17.440 --> 00:32:20.760
at Risk calculations were
too optimistic.

00:32:20.760 --> 00:32:26.020
Companies all over the world
were estimating very small

00:32:26.020 --> 00:32:29.750
numbers here, relative to
what actually happened.

00:32:29.750 --> 00:32:32.315
And that's a problem.

00:32:35.190 --> 00:32:37.840
I wanted to emphasize
core concepts here.

00:32:37.840 --> 00:32:45.110
Intuitive concepts that you
probably already have. One of

00:32:45.110 --> 00:32:48.640
these concepts is something
we'll call the

00:32:48.640 --> 00:32:49.990
law of large numbers.

00:32:59.530 --> 00:33:02.930
And the law of large numbers
says that, there's many

00:33:02.930 --> 00:33:05.010
different ways of formulating
it, but putting it in its

00:33:05.010 --> 00:33:10.390
simplest form, that if I have
a lot of independent shocks,

00:33:10.390 --> 00:33:14.010
and average them out, on average
there's not going to

00:33:14.010 --> 00:33:15.970
be much uncertainty.

00:33:15.970 --> 00:33:21.470
If I flip a coin once, let's
say I'm making a

00:33:21.470 --> 00:33:23.590
bet, plus or minus.

00:33:23.590 --> 00:33:26.280
If it comes up heads, I win a
dollar, if it comes up tails,

00:33:26.280 --> 00:33:27.810
I lose a dollar.

00:33:27.810 --> 00:33:30.820
Well, I have a risk.

00:33:30.820 --> 00:33:33.610
I mean, I have a standard
deviation of $1 in

00:33:33.610 --> 00:33:35.810
my outcome for that.

00:33:35.810 --> 00:33:42.130
But if I do it 100 times and
average the result, there's

00:33:42.130 --> 00:33:44.500
not going to be much
risk at all.

00:33:44.500 --> 00:33:46.240
And that's the law
of large numbers.

00:33:46.240 --> 00:33:52.800
It says that the variance of
the average of n random

00:33:52.800 --> 00:33:55.590
variables that are all
independent and identically

00:33:55.590 --> 00:34:00.510
distributed goes to 0 as the
number of elements in the

00:34:00.510 --> 00:34:03.270
average goes to infinity.

00:34:03.270 --> 00:34:11.990
And so, that's a fundamental
concept that underlies both

00:34:11.990 --> 00:34:14.000
finance and insurance.

00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:19.740
The idea that tossing a coin or
throwing a die in a small

00:34:19.740 --> 00:34:20.840
number of --

00:34:20.840 --> 00:34:24.570
it has uncertainty in a small
number of observations, but

00:34:24.570 --> 00:34:28.340
the uncertainty vanishes in a
large number of observations,

00:34:28.340 --> 00:34:29.870
goes back to the
ancient world.

00:34:29.870 --> 00:34:33.370
Aristotle made this observation,
but he didn't

00:34:33.370 --> 00:34:35.880
have probability theory and he
couldn't carry it further.

00:34:41.300 --> 00:34:46.490
The fundamental concept of
insurance relies on this

00:34:46.490 --> 00:34:47.730
intuitive idea.

00:34:47.730 --> 00:34:50.760
And the idea was intuitive
enough that insurance was

00:34:50.760 --> 00:34:54.440
known and practiced
in ancient times.

00:34:54.440 --> 00:35:01.510
But the insurance concept
depends on independence.

00:35:01.510 --> 00:35:09.380
And so, independence is
something that apparently

00:35:09.380 --> 00:35:11.620
breaks down at times
like these.

00:35:11.620 --> 00:35:16.860
Like these big down crises that
we've seen in the stock

00:35:16.860 --> 00:35:20.500
market, in the two
episodes in the

00:35:20.500 --> 00:35:24.490
beginning of the 20th century.

00:35:24.490 --> 00:35:30.040
So, the law of large numbers has
to do with the idea that

00:35:30.040 --> 00:35:38.720
if I have a large number of
random variables, what is the

00:35:38.720 --> 00:35:40.410
variance of --

00:35:40.410 --> 00:35:51.810
the variance of x1 plus
x2 plus x3 up to xn?

00:35:54.390 --> 00:35:56.660
If they're all independent,
then all of the

00:35:56.660 --> 00:35:58.540
covariances are 0.

00:35:58.540 --> 00:36:07.190
So, it equals the variance of
x1, plus the variance of x2,

00:36:07.190 --> 00:36:09.710
plus the variance of xn.

00:36:09.710 --> 00:36:13.120
There's n terms, I'm not
showing them all.

00:36:13.120 --> 00:36:15.530
OK?

00:36:15.530 --> 00:36:19.790
So, if they all have the same
variance, then the variance of

00:36:19.790 --> 00:36:25.900
the sum of n of them is n times
their variance, OK.

00:36:25.900 --> 00:36:29.290
And that means the standard
deviation, which is the square

00:36:29.290 --> 00:36:33.380
root of the variance, is equal
to the square root of n times

00:36:33.380 --> 00:36:36.660
the standard deviation
of one of them.

00:36:36.660 --> 00:36:39.880
The mean is divided by n.

00:36:39.880 --> 00:36:42.950
So, that means that the standard
deviation of the mean

00:36:42.950 --> 00:36:46.850
is equal to the standard
deviation of one of the x's

00:36:46.850 --> 00:36:48.880
divided by the square
root of n.

00:36:48.880 --> 00:36:53.340
So, as n goes large, you can
see that the standard

00:36:53.340 --> 00:36:56.110
deviation of the
mean goes to 0.

00:36:56.110 --> 00:36:58.910
And that's the law
of large numbers.

00:36:58.910 --> 00:37:01.030
OK.

00:37:01.030 --> 00:37:04.210
But the problem is, so you
know, you can look at a

00:37:04.210 --> 00:37:08.270
financial firm, and they have
returns for a number of years,

00:37:08.270 --> 00:37:11.790
and those returns can be
cumulated to give some sense

00:37:11.790 --> 00:37:14.630
of their total outcome.

00:37:14.630 --> 00:37:20.810
But does the total outcome
really behave properly?

00:37:20.810 --> 00:37:25.340
Does it become certain over
a longer interval of time?

00:37:25.340 --> 00:37:31.460
Well apparently not, because
of the possibility that the

00:37:31.460 --> 00:37:34.870
observations are not
independent.

00:37:34.870 --> 00:37:39.530
So, we want to move from
analysis of variance to

00:37:39.530 --> 00:37:41.180
something that's more --

00:37:41.180 --> 00:37:48.810
I told you that VaR came in 1987
or thereabouts, after the

00:37:48.810 --> 00:37:51.150
