00:58:58.920 --> 00:59:03.750
So, I want to move on now to
next topic, which is outliers,

00:59:03.750 --> 00:59:09.690
and talk about another
assumption that is made in

00:59:09.690 --> 00:59:12.500
finance traditionally that
turned out to be

00:59:12.500 --> 00:59:16.140
wrong in this episode.

00:59:16.140 --> 00:59:20.250
And the assumption is that
random shocks to the financial

00:59:20.250 --> 00:59:23.890
economy are normally
distributed.

00:59:23.890 --> 00:59:27.630
You must have heard of the
normal distribution.

00:59:27.630 --> 00:59:32.960
This is the bell-shaped, the
famous bell-shaped curve, that

00:59:32.960 --> 00:59:37.890
was discovered by the
mathematician Gauss over a

00:59:37.890 --> 00:59:39.810
hundred years ago.

00:59:39.810 --> 00:59:44.780
The bell-shaped curve
is thought to be --

00:59:44.780 --> 00:59:50.330
this particular bell-shaped
curve which is the --

00:59:54.940 --> 00:59:56.820
the log of this curve
is a parabola.

00:59:56.820 --> 00:59:58.780
It's a particular mathematical
function.

01:00:01.560 --> 01:00:06.310
The curve is thought by
statisticians to recur in

01:00:06.310 --> 01:00:08.385
nature many different ways.

01:00:08.385 --> 01:00:12.500
It has a certain probability
law.

01:00:12.500 --> 01:00:18.260
So, I have plotted two normal
distributions, and I have them

01:00:18.260 --> 01:00:20.840
for two different standard
deviations.

01:00:20.840 --> 01:00:24.290
One of them, black line, is the
standard deviation of 3,

01:00:24.290 --> 01:00:26.460
and the other one, the pink
line, is the standard

01:00:26.460 --> 01:00:29.000
deviation of 1.

01:00:29.000 --> 01:00:30.820
But they both look the same,
they're just scaled

01:00:30.820 --> 01:00:31.850
differently.

01:00:31.850 --> 01:00:35.290
And these distributions have
the property that the area

01:00:35.290 --> 01:00:39.520
under the curve is equal to 1
and the area between any two

01:00:39.520 --> 01:00:43.730
points, say between minus 5 and
minus 10, the area under

01:00:43.730 --> 01:00:47.480
this curve is the probability
that the random variable falls

01:00:47.480 --> 01:00:50.590
between minus 5 and minus 10.

01:00:50.590 --> 01:00:54.450
So, a lot of probability theory
works on the assumption

01:00:54.450 --> 01:01:00.000
that variables are normally
distributed.

01:01:00.000 --> 01:01:05.570
But random variables have a
habit of not behaving that

01:01:05.570 --> 01:01:11.530
way, especially in finance it
seems. And so, we had a

01:01:11.530 --> 01:01:15.060
mathematician here in the Yale
math department, Benoit

01:01:15.060 --> 01:01:19.870
Mandelbrot, who was really the
discoverer of this concept,

01:01:19.870 --> 01:01:24.152
and I think the most important
figure in it.

01:01:24.152 --> 01:01:24.328
[correction: Pierre Paul Levy
invented the concept, as

01:01:24.328 --> 01:01:24.438
discussed in the
next lecture.]

01:01:24.438 --> 01:01:31.850
He said that in nature the
normal distribution is not the

01:01:31.850 --> 01:01:35.260
only distribution that occurs,
and that especially in certain

01:01:35.260 --> 01:01:39.230
kinds of circumstances we have
more fat-tailed distributions.

01:01:39.230 --> 01:01:44.160
So, this blue line is the normal
distribution, and the

01:01:44.160 --> 01:01:47.990
pink line that I've shown is a
fat-tailed distribution that

01:01:47.990 --> 01:01:51.100
Mandelbrot talked about,
called the Cauchy

01:01:51.100 --> 01:01:52.250
distribution.

01:01:52.250 --> 01:01:53.890
You see how it differs?

01:01:53.890 --> 01:01:57.860
The pink line looks pretty
much the same.

01:01:57.860 --> 01:02:00.230
They're both bell-shaped
curves, right?

01:02:00.230 --> 01:02:05.350
But the pink line has
tremendously large probability

01:02:05.350 --> 01:02:07.710
of being far out.

01:02:07.710 --> 01:02:10.960
These are the tails of
the distribution.

01:02:10.960 --> 01:02:17.140
So, if you observe a random
variable that looks --

01:02:17.140 --> 01:02:20.320
you observe it for a while,
maybe you get 100

01:02:20.320 --> 01:02:24.960
observations, you probably can't
tell it apart very well

01:02:24.960 --> 01:02:26.170
from a normal distribution.

01:02:26.170 --> 01:02:28.910
Whether it's Cauchy or normal,
they look about the same.

01:02:28.910 --> 01:02:32.780
The way you find out that
they're not the same, is that

01:02:32.780 --> 01:02:35.680
in extremely rare circumstances
there'll be a

01:02:35.680 --> 01:02:40.700
sudden major jump in the
variable that you might have

01:02:40.700 --> 01:02:41.950
