If it's a normal distribution
and it fits the central

01:05:36.820 --> 01:05:39.600
portion, it would say
it's virtually zero.

01:05:39.600 --> 01:05:41.510
It couldn't happen.

01:05:41.510 --> 01:05:49.410
Anyone have any idea what
happened on October 30, 1929?

01:05:49.410 --> 01:05:53.190
It's obvious to me, but it's
not obvious to you.

01:05:53.190 --> 01:05:54.950
I'm asking you to --

01:05:54.950 --> 01:05:57.350
I won't ask.

01:05:57.350 --> 01:05:59.430
What happened in October, does
anyone know what happened in

01:05:59.430 --> 01:06:01.190
October 1929?

01:06:01.190 --> 01:06:03.595
STUDENT: That must be right
before the crash.

01:06:03.595 --> 01:06:05.230
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER:
You're close.

01:06:05.230 --> 01:06:06.980
You're right.

01:06:06.980 --> 01:06:07.650
But someone else?

01:06:07.650 --> 01:06:07.960
STUDENT: Wasn't it the rebound
after the crash?

01:06:07.960 --> 01:06:11.160
PROFESSOR ROBERT SHILLER: Yes,
absolutely, it was the rebound

01:06:11.160 --> 01:06:12.730
after the crash.

01:06:12.730 --> 01:06:16.970
The stock market crash of 1929
had two consecutive days.

01:06:16.970 --> 01:06:19.460
Boy is that probability,
independence

01:06:19.460 --> 01:06:20.540
doesn't seem right.

01:06:20.540 --> 01:06:24.870
It went down about 12% on
October 28, and then the next

01:06:24.870 --> 01:06:26.240
day it did it again.

01:06:26.240 --> 01:06:27.400
What's going on here?

01:06:27.400 --> 01:06:30.170
We were down like
24% in two days.

01:06:30.170 --> 01:06:33.540
People got up on the 30th and
said, oh my God, is it going

01:06:33.540 --> 01:06:34.880
to do that again?

01:06:34.880 --> 01:06:36.840
But it did just the opposite.

01:06:36.840 --> 01:06:39.130
It was going totally wild.

01:06:39.130 --> 01:06:41.655
So, we don't know whether
covariance broke down or not.

01:06:41.655 --> 01:06:44.160
I guess it didn't, because it
rebounded, and that was the

01:06:44.160 --> 01:06:46.510
biggest one-day increase ever.

01:06:46.510 --> 01:06:50.600
But if that weren't enough,
however, let's go back to

01:06:50.600 --> 01:06:53.930
October 19, 1987.

01:06:53.930 --> 01:06:58.760
It went down 20.47%
in one day.

01:06:58.760 --> 01:07:00.660
It went down even
more on the Dow.

01:07:00.660 --> 01:07:03.360
Some people say it went down
more than that, didn't it?

01:07:03.360 --> 01:07:06.970
But on the S&amp;P that's how
much it went down.

01:07:06.970 --> 01:07:10.530
So, I figured, well if this were
normally distributed with

01:07:10.530 --> 01:07:14.310
the standard deviation suggested
by this, what's the

01:07:14.310 --> 01:07:20.700
probability of a decline
that's that negative?

01:07:20.700 --> 01:07:24.650
It's 10 to the minus 71 power.

01:07:24.650 --> 01:07:25.910
1 over 10.

01:07:25.910 --> 01:07:29.750
So, you take 1 and you divide
that by 1 followed by

01:07:29.750 --> 01:07:31.730
seventy-one zeros.

01:07:31.730 --> 01:07:34.160
That's an awfully
small number.

01:07:34.160 --> 01:07:37.400
If you believe in normality,
October 19,

01:07:37.400 --> 01:07:40.110
1987 couldn't happen.

01:07:40.110 --> 01:07:40.950
But there it is.

01:07:40.950 --> 01:07:41.690
It happened.

01:07:41.690 --> 01:07:45.300
And in fact, I was, I told you
I've been teaching this course

01:07:45.300 --> 01:07:47.510
for 25 years.

01:07:47.510 --> 01:07:52.280
I was giving a lecture, not in
this room, but nearby here,

01:07:52.280 --> 01:07:55.090
and I was talking about
something else.

01:07:55.090 --> 01:07:58.530
And a student had a
transistor radio.

01:07:58.530 --> 01:08:01.530
Remember transistor radios?

01:08:01.530 --> 01:08:04.160
And he was holding it up
and listening to it.

01:08:04.160 --> 01:08:05.875
Then he raised his
hand and said, do

01:08:05.875 --> 01:08:08.660
you know what's happening?

01:08:08.660 --> 01:08:11.510
He said the stock market is
totally falling apart.

01:08:11.510 --> 01:08:13.950
It just came as a complete
surprise to me.

01:08:13.950 --> 01:08:17.545
So, after class, I didn't
go back to my office.

01:08:17.545 --> 01:08:20.070
I went downtown to
Merrill Lynch.

01:08:20.070 --> 01:08:23.400
And I walked up, it's a
story I like to tell.

01:08:23.400 --> 01:08:24.990
It's not that good.

01:08:24.990 --> 01:08:28.250
I walked up and I talked to a
stockbroker there, and I said,

01:08:28.250 --> 01:08:31.280
I was about to say something,
but he didn't let me talk.

01:08:31.280 --> 01:08:33.490
He said, don't panic.

01:08:33.490 --> 01:08:38.400
He thought that I had shown up
as a someone who was losing

01:08:38.400 --> 01:08:41.660
everything, his life savings
all in one day.

01:08:41.660 --> 01:08:44.080
And he said, don't worry,
it's not going to --

01:08:44.080 --> 01:08:47.010
it's going to rebound.

01:08:47.010 --> 01:08:48.300
It didn't rebound.

01:08:48.300 --> 01:08:53.750
I showed up at lunchtime
and it kept going down.

01:08:53.750 --> 01:08:55.900
So, anyway, there was
something wrong with

01:08:55.900 --> 01:08:57.430
independence.

01:08:57.430 --> 01:08:59.410
Let me just recap.

01:08:59.410 --> 01:09:03.320
The two themes are that
independence leads to the law

01:09:03.320 --> 01:09:06.680
of large numbers, and it leads
to some sort of stability.

01:09:06.680 --> 01:09:08.870
Either independence
through time or

01:09:08.870 --> 01:09:10.720
independence across stocks.

01:09:10.720 --> 01:09:13.640
So, if you diversify through
time or you diversify across

01:09:13.640 --> 01:09:15.950
stocks, you're supposed
to be safe.

01:09:15.950 --> 01:09:19.450
But that's not what happened in
this crisis and that's the

01:09:19.450 --> 01:09:22.180
big question.

01:09:22.180 --> 01:09:24.460
And then it's fat-tails, which
is kind of related.

01:09:24.460 --> 01:09:29.050
But it's that distributions
fool you.

01:09:29.050 --> 01:09:32.230
You get big incredible shocks
that you thought couldn't

01:09:32.230 --> 01:09:35.230
happen, and they just come
up with a certain low

01:09:35.230 --> 01:09:38.480
probability, but with a certain
regularity in finance.

01:09:38.480 --> 01:09:39.510
All right, I'll stop there.

01:09:39.510 --> 01:09:41.865
I'll see you on next Wednesday.

